WEBVTT

00:01.536 --> 00:04.503
<i>[jazz music]</i>

00:04.539 --> 00:11.544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:18.452 --> 00:21.153
[cheering and applause]

00:21.189 --> 00:22.888
<i>- From the
Penn & Teller Theater</i>

00:22.924 --> 00:24.824
<i>at the Rio Hotel
in Las Vegas,</i>

00:24.859 --> 00:30.095
<i>here's our host:
Alyson Hannigan!</i>

00:30.131 --> 00:33.132
[cheering and applause]

00:41.409 --> 00:43.943
- Welcome to
Penn & Teller: Fool Us.

00:43.978 --> 00:46.278
If you're watching our show
for the first time,

00:46.314 --> 00:47.479
where have you been?

00:47.515 --> 00:49.582
You've missed hundreds
of amazing tricks.

00:49.650 --> 00:51.250
Oh, sorry.
I mean,

00:51.285 --> 00:52.918
thank you for joining us.
[laughter]

00:52.954 --> 00:54.653
Well, this is how
the show works:

00:54.689 --> 00:56.689
magicians try to fool
Penn and Teller

00:56.724 --> 00:59.725
in order to win an
all-expense-paid trip to Vegas

00:59.760 --> 01:02.494
to perform in their
world-famous magic show.

01:02.530 --> 01:03.863
So, let's begin.

01:03.898 --> 01:07.032
Ladies and gentlemen,
Penn and Teller!

01:07.068 --> 01:10.035
[cheering and applause]

01:10.071 --> 01:13.038
<i>[jazz music]</i>

01:13.074 --> 01:15.975
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:16.010 --> 01:18.277
Hello.
Oh, hi!

01:18.312 --> 01:20.613
[laughs]

01:20.648 --> 01:23.282
[cheering and applause]

01:23.317 --> 01:25.517
Penn and Teller
look comfortable.

01:25.553 --> 01:26.986
Well, maybe too comfortable.

01:27.021 --> 01:29.355
Are they ready
for our first magician?

01:29.390 --> 01:31.557
Let's meet him and find out.

01:31.592 --> 01:33.726
<i>[fireworks crackle]</i>

01:33.761 --> 01:35.961
- My name is Ryan Chandler.
I'm from Omaha, Nebraska.

01:35.997 --> 01:38.230
<i>By day I'm a teacher,
and by night</i>

01:38.266 --> 01:40.032
<i>I do magic and music.</i>

01:40.067 --> 01:42.468
Just like creating a song,
it's the same thing

01:42.503 --> 01:44.270
<i>creating a trick or a routine.</i>

01:44.305 --> 01:46.505
<i>You want to put in
your own formula,</i>

01:46.540 --> 01:48.641
<i>and try to just
figure something out</i>

01:48.676 --> 01:51.543
<i>that's artistically unique
to you.</i>

01:51.579 --> 01:53.012
The trick that I'm doing
for Penn and Teller,

01:53.047 --> 01:54.947
it's like something just--
like a lightning bolt

01:54.982 --> 01:56.115
or something
just touched me on the top

01:56.150 --> 01:57.516
of the head and said,
Here it is.

01:57.551 --> 01:59.084
And it just happened.
It's like, I can't even

01:59.120 --> 02:00.886
take credit for it--I don't
even know how it happened.

02:00.922 --> 02:02.588
<i>And I've being doing music
forever,</i>

02:02.623 --> 02:04.490
<i>and I've been doing magic
for a long time.</i>

02:04.525 --> 02:06.091
The two storms
just came together,

02:06.127 --> 02:08.961
and that's what's
gonna happen tonight.

02:08.996 --> 02:12.998
[cheers and applause]

02:13.034 --> 02:15.034
- Please welcome
the musical magic

02:15.069 --> 02:17.069
of Ryan Chandler!

02:17.104 --> 02:21.206
[cheering and applause]

02:21.242 --> 02:23.375
- All right.
Thank you for having me.

02:23.411 --> 02:26.111
Two passions of mine
are magic and music.

02:26.147 --> 02:28.147
And right now,
I'd like to try something

02:28.182 --> 02:29.581
using a little bit of both.

02:29.617 --> 02:31.050
Alyson, would you please
join me on stage?

02:31.085 --> 02:32.518
- Sure.
- Ladies and gentlemen, Alyson.

02:32.553 --> 02:34.320
[cheers and applause]
That's enough!

02:34.355 --> 02:36.121
That's enough.
- [laughs]

02:36.157 --> 02:38.791
- It's still my trick.
[laughter]

02:38.826 --> 02:40.960
Alyson, here's
what we're gonna do.

02:40.995 --> 02:42.394
It starts out
with a deck of cards.

02:42.430 --> 02:44.063
All the cards are different.

02:44.098 --> 02:45.831
All you're gonna do
is just touch one card

02:45.866 --> 02:48.200
that you feel drawn to, okay?
Go ahead.

02:48.235 --> 02:49.868
- Um...
- Any card you'd like.

02:49.904 --> 02:51.136
Okay.

02:51.172 --> 02:52.471
Now, just so these guys
over here know

02:52.506 --> 02:54.273
that it's a free selection,
why don't you go ahead

02:54.308 --> 02:56.642
and change your mind.
- [laughs] Okay.

02:56.677 --> 02:57.876
- Okay? Perfect.

02:57.912 --> 02:59.244
All right, go ahead.

02:59.280 --> 03:01.547
Show it to no one,
not even the camera, okay?

03:01.582 --> 03:02.681
Got it?
- Can I look at it?

03:02.717 --> 03:04.416
- You like it?
Yep, go ahead.

03:04.452 --> 03:05.751
- Mm-kay.
- All right,

03:05.786 --> 03:08.053
so that was the card portion
of the magic trick.

03:08.089 --> 03:09.621
[laughter]
Now I need to get

03:09.657 --> 03:11.023
to the music portion.

03:11.058 --> 03:13.359
So if we could, uh,
have Penn and Teller

03:13.394 --> 03:15.094
please join me on stage.
Come on up.

03:15.129 --> 03:18.030
[cheers and applause]

03:18.065 --> 03:21.867
All right, so...

03:21.902 --> 03:23.535
- That's my axe.
- You've got your bass, yeah.

03:23.571 --> 03:25.504
- That's my bass.
You want me to take it out

03:25.539 --> 03:27.573
of the, uh, stand?
- Teller, nice to meet you.

03:27.608 --> 03:29.475
Now, uh...

03:29.510 --> 03:32.511
You don't talk,
so I wanted to find a way

03:32.546 --> 03:33.812
to incorporate you
into the trick.

03:33.848 --> 03:35.547
so I brought out a chime.

03:35.583 --> 03:37.950
And then, uh,
a musical instrument for you.

03:37.985 --> 03:40.552
So you just strike the chime.
You wanna give it a try?

03:40.588 --> 03:42.121
[ding]

03:42.156 --> 03:43.155
Yep.
[cheers and applause]

03:43.190 --> 03:44.890
Okay, yeah. Guys.

03:44.925 --> 03:46.458
Save it for me at the end.
[laughter]

03:46.494 --> 03:47.726
All right.
[laughter]

03:47.762 --> 03:49.461
And then we have your bass.
- This is mine.

03:49.497 --> 03:50.796
- We stole this from you.
- Shall I take it?

03:50.831 --> 03:52.765
- Yeah, um, go ahead.

03:52.800 --> 03:54.333
Just make sure it still works.

03:54.368 --> 03:57.036
- I--I believe it does.
[plays bass]

03:57.071 --> 03:58.470
- Yeah.
[applause]

03:58.506 --> 04:00.439
This guy's good.
He's a professional.

04:00.474 --> 04:02.341
All right,
so we're ready to roll.

04:02.376 --> 04:04.643
Uh--
That's enough, Penn.

04:04.678 --> 04:06.578
Okay, so...
[laughter]

04:06.614 --> 04:07.813
[plays flat note]
Now we go

04:07.848 --> 04:09.548
to the teaching portion.
I'm a teacher, by day.

04:09.583 --> 04:11.583
You know all about that.

04:11.619 --> 04:16.654
This is a truly magical piece
of music equipment

04:16.690 --> 04:18.390
known as a "looper."

04:18.426 --> 04:21.793
What it allows you to do
is you can record something

04:21.829 --> 04:24.163
and then if you just
press a button, it'll play it

04:24.198 --> 04:26.932
over, and over...
[Penn plays a note]

04:26.967 --> 04:31.036
And over again, endlessly,
as if in a loop.

04:31.072 --> 04:32.905
So that's what we're gonna
go ahead and try, right now.

04:32.940 --> 04:34.339
Okay?

04:34.375 --> 04:37.276
Just to be clear, everything
that you are about to hear

04:37.311 --> 04:39.611
is happening in real time.

04:39.647 --> 04:43.549
Magic in the form of music.

04:43.584 --> 04:45.951
Track 1 will be me.
Alyson, you'll be on Track 2,

04:45.986 --> 04:47.386
so get ready to roll.
[laughter]

04:47.455 --> 04:50.923
Uh, Track 3 is gonna be
our Penn and Teller track.

04:50.958 --> 04:52.257
So you guys are gonna
go together on that one.

04:52.293 --> 04:53.325
- We're sharing a track?
- Yeah.

04:53.360 --> 04:54.426
- Okay.
- And then I'm gonna go

04:54.462 --> 04:56.361
on Track 4, here.
Round us up, okay?

04:56.397 --> 04:59.298
- Okay.
- Okay, here we go.

04:59.333 --> 05:03.001
[beat boxes]

05:03.037 --> 05:06.905
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:06.941 --> 05:09.274
[recording plays
over speakers]

05:09.310 --> 05:11.076
Magic?
[applause]

05:11.112 --> 05:13.412
Yeah, okay.

05:13.447 --> 05:15.647
All right,
we'll go to Track 2, here.

05:15.683 --> 05:18.884
Alyson, I just want you
to go ahead and say your name.

05:18.919 --> 05:20.252
Okay? Here we go.

05:20.287 --> 05:21.653
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:21.689 --> 05:23.889
- Alyson.
- Say, "Hi, my name is Alyson."

05:23.924 --> 05:26.925
- Hi, my name is Alyson.
- What's your favorite color?

05:26.961 --> 05:29.595
- Purple.

05:29.630 --> 05:31.663
<i>Alyson.</i>

05:31.699 --> 05:33.465
<i>Hi, my name is Alyson.</i>

05:33.501 --> 05:36.001
[laughs]
- Lead vocalist, right there.

05:36.036 --> 05:38.036
All right, Track 3.
The Penn and Teller track.

05:38.072 --> 05:40.606
I'm gonna have Teller start off
with the chime.

05:40.641 --> 05:45.277
All right, here we go.

05:45.312 --> 05:49.181
[rings chime in beat]

05:49.216 --> 05:50.649
- All right, that's enough.
That's enough.

05:50.684 --> 05:52.818
[laughter]

05:52.853 --> 05:54.920
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:54.955 --> 05:56.822
All right, and then
we got Penn on the base.

05:56.857 --> 05:59.124
We're still on Track 3, here.

05:59.160 --> 06:01.827
So here we go.

06:01.862 --> 06:04.830
[plays funky bass beat]

06:04.865 --> 06:11.870
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:12.406 --> 06:15.073
<i>- Purple.</i>

06:15.109 --> 06:16.942
<i>Alyson.</i>

06:16.977 --> 06:18.710
<i>Hi, my name is Alyson.</i>

06:18.746 --> 06:21.180
- So you can hear the bass;
you can hear everything.

06:21.215 --> 06:22.614
All right.

06:22.650 --> 06:25.884
And now, I'm gonna go ahead,
for the fourth track--

06:25.920 --> 06:28.053
I'm not gonna lie, this is
gonna be a little creepy.

06:28.088 --> 06:30.689
Little weird, little different.

06:30.724 --> 06:34.426
Here we go.

06:34.461 --> 06:37.429
[strange whispering into mic]

06:37.464 --> 06:44.469
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:46.507 --> 06:49.508
[laughter]

06:53.847 --> 06:55.714
Okay, Penn.
Since you are a musician--

06:55.749 --> 06:58.817
I know both of you guys do--
uh, can you put the bass back?

06:58.852 --> 07:01.253
And then I'll go ahead
and I'll take your chime.

07:01.288 --> 07:03.488
[track continues to play]

07:03.524 --> 07:05.090
And then I'm gonna let you
come over, and actually play

07:05.125 --> 07:06.625
with the looper a little bit.
- Okay.

07:06.660 --> 07:08.727
- Okay?
So, uh, come on over.

07:08.762 --> 07:10.996
Now, they say
when you take an old record

07:11.031 --> 07:13.031
and you spin it backwards,
sometimes you get

07:13.067 --> 07:14.499
that hidden message.

07:14.535 --> 07:17.769
Teller, do you see that
reverse button right there?

07:17.805 --> 07:20.138
We're gonna go ahead--
hit the reverse button,

07:20.174 --> 07:22.608
we'll hear it in reverse.

07:22.643 --> 07:25.077
[track plays backwards]

07:25.112 --> 07:27.179
And Penn, if you'd like,
go ahead and slowly drag back

07:27.214 --> 07:28.213
each track.

07:28.249 --> 07:32.684
[whispered]
<i>Of...Spades...</i>

07:32.720 --> 07:37.256
<i>Five...Of...</i>

07:37.291 --> 07:40.759
<i>Spades...</i>

07:40.794 --> 07:43.495
<i>Five...</i>

07:43.530 --> 07:45.030
<i>Of...</i>

07:45.065 --> 07:46.798
<i>Spades...
</i> Now, Alyson,

07:46.834 --> 07:48.133
you picked a card
right at the beginning.

07:48.168 --> 07:49.701
Any card you wanted.
For the first time, go ahead

07:49.737 --> 07:51.303
and show everyone your card.

07:51.338 --> 07:53.572
<i>Five...Of... Spades...</i>

07:53.607 --> 07:55.140
Got it.
[cheering and applause]

07:55.175 --> 07:58.610
Ladies and gentlemen,
Alyson, Penn, and Teller.

07:58.646 --> 08:01.713
- Ryan Chandler!

08:01.749 --> 08:04.783
[cheering and applause]

08:04.818 --> 08:07.286
Ah, well,
you earned that applause.

08:07.321 --> 08:08.754
- Thank you, thank you.
- Yeah.

08:08.789 --> 08:10.689
- That's incredible...
- Thank you.

08:10.724 --> 08:12.190
- Very impressive.

08:12.226 --> 08:15.560
I was a little worried
when you gave me my own track.

08:15.596 --> 08:16.762
Like, I wasn't--
- Oh, I wasn't--

08:16.797 --> 08:18.063
I had confidence in you.
- Aww, thanks.

08:18.098 --> 08:19.831
- I knew you'd do it.
Hit it out of the park.

08:19.867 --> 08:22.200
- Did you ever want
to just be a musician?

08:22.236 --> 08:24.336
- Uh, absolutely.
I just wasn't good enough.

08:24.371 --> 08:26.104
[laughter]
And, uh...

08:26.140 --> 08:28.340
Same thing with magic.
So I just try to do

08:28.375 --> 08:29.941
a little bit of both,
and hopefully you guys

08:29.977 --> 08:31.610
are entertained by it, so.
- [laughs]

08:31.645 --> 08:33.912
Or ma--maybe you're great
at both.

08:33.947 --> 08:35.881
And--and you teach?

08:35.916 --> 08:38.082
- Yep, I'm a teacher by day,
so...

08:38.118 --> 08:41.419
- What do you teach?
- I teach, uh, middle school.

08:41.455 --> 08:43.655
Six--grades six through eight.
- Oh, wow.

08:43.691 --> 08:45.657
- And it's kind of fun,
When I get the sixth graders,

08:45.693 --> 08:46.825
they don't know I do magic.

08:46.860 --> 08:48.894
So I just kind of, like,
make things disappear

08:48.929 --> 08:51.563
without letting them know.
- [laughs]

08:51.598 --> 08:54.132
- So they'll be sitting there,
and I'll make something vanish.

08:54.168 --> 08:56.268
And then I'll walk off.
And then I'll--

08:56.303 --> 08:57.402
I'll say, "Do you have that?"

08:57.438 --> 08:58.603
And they're like, "Wh--
where'd it go?"

08:58.639 --> 09:01.239
- [laughs]
- I'm like, "I don't know."

09:01.275 --> 09:03.375
- All right.
Let's see if Penn and Teller

09:03.410 --> 09:04.710
know all the beats
to your trick.

09:04.745 --> 09:06.178
- All right, sounds good.

09:06.213 --> 09:08.580
- Uh, boy, uh--
It's--it's really great.

09:08.615 --> 09:09.815
So nice to see that.

09:09.850 --> 09:11.416
And so nice
to see looping used.

09:11.452 --> 09:12.651
I love--I love looping.

09:12.686 --> 09:14.319
And a, uh,--
You know the Beatles

09:14.355 --> 09:17.656
did a, uh-- "White Album,"
and on it was "Revolution 9."

09:17.691 --> 09:20.792
If you played that backwards,
you got, "Tur-me-on-dedmen,"

09:20.828 --> 09:23.028
Tur-me-on-dedmen,
Tur-me-on-dedmen.

09:23.063 --> 09:24.996
And I would play that
on my tape, uh--

09:25.032 --> 09:28.033
on my, uh, turntable--
way back when we had those--

09:28.068 --> 09:30.569
backwards over and over again
till I could do it.

09:30.604 --> 09:32.704
And then I got a tape recorder,
then tested it,

09:32.740 --> 09:35.674
so I could actually say
number nine backwards.

09:35.709 --> 09:38.610
Made the whole thing very,
very plausible, and very good.

09:38.645 --> 09:41.413
But you know,
like all good magicians,

09:41.448 --> 09:43.749
you told a lie right up top.

09:43.784 --> 09:46.551
Right at the very beginning,
really early on.

09:46.587 --> 09:48.420
One that
everybody else believed,

09:48.455 --> 09:51.923
and, uh, we even believed
until we saw the trick.

09:51.959 --> 09:53.258
So I'm gonna give you--

09:53.293 --> 09:55.227
I've already told you
that part of that.

09:55.262 --> 09:56.762
But I'll give you
the other part of that,

09:56.797 --> 09:59.464
in, uh--uh, backwards.

09:59.500 --> 10:01.600
Ee-sorf.

10:01.635 --> 10:03.602
Ee-sorf.
[laughter]

10:03.637 --> 10:04.770
Wasn't it?
- Uh...

10:04.805 --> 10:06.705
- Do you understand
ee-sorf?

10:06.740 --> 10:09.174
- I--I understand that, yeah.
Completely.

10:09.209 --> 10:10.942
I'm not as good at code...
- [laughing]

10:10.978 --> 10:13.078
- You understand?
- Welcome to my world.

10:13.113 --> 10:15.414
- I'm a middle school teacher.
- [laughing]

10:15.449 --> 10:17.516
- Okay, so it sounds like
they know how you did it.

10:17.551 --> 10:19.151
- Yes. Yes, absolutely.
Very good.

10:19.186 --> 10:21.720
- Well, thank you so much.
Ryan Chandler!

10:21.755 --> 10:23.522
- Thank you very much.
Thank you.

10:23.557 --> 10:25.123
[cheering and applause]

10:25.159 --> 10:27.292
- Don't you...
No, no!

10:27.327 --> 10:29.928
Get away from there!
- [laughs]

10:29.963 --> 10:32.264
- After the break,
Penn and Teller try

10:32.299 --> 10:33.598
to bust more magicians.

10:33.634 --> 10:35.767
And later, they'll perform
a trick of their own.

10:35.803 --> 10:37.169
Don't go anywhere.

10:37.204 --> 10:40.172
<i>[jazz music]</i>

10:40.207 --> 10:42.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:44.111 --> 10:46.611
<i>[jazz music]</i>

10:46.647 --> 10:49.581
[cheering and applause]

10:49.616 --> 10:51.049
- This next magician

10:51.084 --> 10:53.718
performs magic
in six languages.

10:53.754 --> 10:55.487
Let's hope he chooses
the right one

10:55.522 --> 10:57.055
to fool Penn and Teller.

10:57.090 --> 10:59.090
<i>[fireworks crackling]</i>

10:59.126 --> 11:00.559
<i>- I'm Ryan Hayashi.</i>

11:00.594 --> 11:01.927
<i>[dramatic gong flair]</i>

11:01.962 --> 11:03.662
<i>When I was a kid,
I had two heroes:</i>

11:03.697 --> 11:06.565
Bruce Lee
and David Copperfield.

11:06.600 --> 11:08.500
They inspired me.
I wanted to do what they did.

11:08.535 --> 11:09.901
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

11:09.937 --> 11:12.270
<i>The martial arts and magic
are very similar</i>

11:12.306 --> 11:14.706
<i>because they both come
from older traditions</i>

11:14.741 --> 11:16.541
<i>that have been passed down
over centuries.</i>

11:16.577 --> 11:18.777
<i>You have to master
certain movements</i>

11:18.812 --> 11:20.679
<i>to the point that
there's precision,</i>

11:20.714 --> 11:22.447
<i>but at the same time
having a flow,</i>

11:22.483 --> 11:24.749
<i>and making it your own.</i>

11:24.785 --> 11:26.718
<i>The first time
that I actually combined magic</i>

11:26.753 --> 11:28.053
<i>and the martial arts</i>

11:28.088 --> 11:30.922
was "the Samurai Madman
of Magic."

11:30.958 --> 11:32.691
<i>I cut up vegetables
around people's heads,</i>

11:32.726 --> 11:34.426
blindfolded,
without killing them.

11:34.461 --> 11:37.829
<i>Now, I'm shedding
my samurai character</i>

11:37.865 --> 11:39.731
<i>and stripping down
my performance</i>

11:39.766 --> 11:41.566
<i>to magic in its purest form:</i>

11:41.602 --> 11:43.702
<i>Showing off what I can do
with a few coins</i>

11:43.737 --> 11:45.337
<i>that fit in my pocket.</i>

11:45.372 --> 11:49.441
[cheering and applause]

11:49.476 --> 11:53.912
- Please welcome the coin magic
of Ryan Hayashi!

11:53.947 --> 11:55.547
[dramatic gong flair]

11:55.582 --> 11:58.884
- [speaking Japanese]

11:58.919 --> 12:01.853
That's Japanese for,
Time to get my freak on.

12:01.889 --> 12:03.588
[laughter]
How you guys doing?

12:03.624 --> 12:05.891
[cheering]

12:05.926 --> 12:07.292
Yeah.

12:07.327 --> 12:10.028
When I was a kid in the 1980s,
I saw Penn and Teller

12:10.063 --> 12:11.897
on television,
performing an act

12:11.932 --> 12:14.332
with just a pencil
and a cigarette.

12:14.368 --> 12:16.735
This act fooled me and
taught me the basics of magic.

12:16.770 --> 12:18.503
So, Penn, Teller.

12:18.539 --> 12:21.206
