I love that this is based
on a simple trick

27:45.798 --> 27:48.265
that young magicians can do.

27:48.301 --> 27:51.402
And when they watch you do it,
they will have no idea

27:51.437 --> 27:52.770
how it's done.
- Yeah.

27:52.805 --> 27:54.138
- It's just great,
it's just great

27:54.173 --> 27:56.207
that it starts out going,
Oh, yeah, I know, I know.

27:56.242 --> 27:59.677
And there's a lot of smug
14-year-olds watching this

27:59.712 --> 28:02.279
who then are shut up
by this routine.

28:02.315 --> 28:04.415
[laughter]
Uh, you add the candle,

28:04.450 --> 28:07.518
and that candle is so, uh,
so helpful to the routine.

28:07.553 --> 28:09.353
It's not just the table
floating around.

28:09.388 --> 28:11.021
There's also the candle there.

28:11.057 --> 28:14.325
And the vanish at the end
we weren't expecting.

28:14.360 --> 28:16.126
So we had to, uh--
we had to scramble

28:16.162 --> 28:19.163
a little bit on that.
We have an idea where it is.

28:19.198 --> 28:22.266
And I--I hate
to even be cagey about this

28:22.301 --> 28:26.103
'cause it's so good,
and it's so based on stuff

28:26.138 --> 28:28.272
that some young people
will know.

28:28.307 --> 28:30.407
But I want them
to be murdered by it...

28:30.443 --> 28:31.675
I want them to be killed by it.
- [laughing]

28:31.711 --> 28:33.143
- So I don't want
to give away anything,

28:33.179 --> 28:36.280
even in code, but I think
we know where that table went.

28:36.315 --> 28:38.716
- Okay.
- Yeah--just to make sure...

28:38.751 --> 28:39.717
- Okay.
- 'Cause we could be wrong

28:39.752 --> 28:40.951
on this...
- Okay.

28:40.987 --> 28:42.286
- But just to make sure,
let Teller whisper it.

28:42.321 --> 28:44.021
I just don't want anybody
at home to hear this,

28:44.056 --> 28:48.192
'cause I want them
to worry about it a little bit.

28:48.227 --> 28:49.393
- [whispered]
Yes.

28:49.428 --> 28:50.895
Yes.
- Aww.

28:50.930 --> 28:52.129
- Yes.
[audience groans]

28:52.164 --> 28:55.199
- [laughing]
- So they know how it's done?

28:55.234 --> 28:57.935
- They know how it's done,
but I am--

28:57.970 --> 28:59.970
I sure hoped
I enchanted everybody.

29:00.006 --> 29:01.839
- Oh, definitely.
- You sure did.

29:01.874 --> 29:04.542
- Losander,
ladies and gentlemen!

29:04.577 --> 29:06.844
Thank you.
- Thank you, guys.

29:06.879 --> 29:09.880
[cheering and applause]

29:09.916 --> 29:12.249
- We'll keep putting
Penn and Teller to the test

29:12.285 --> 29:13.350
when we come back.

29:13.386 --> 29:14.752
Stick around.

29:14.787 --> 29:17.755
<i>[jazz music]</i>

29:17.790 --> 29:19.723
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:21.694 --> 29:24.328
<i>[jazz music]</i>

29:24.363 --> 29:26.797
[cheering and applause]

29:26.832 --> 29:28.532
- Welcome back to "Fool Us."

29:28.568 --> 29:31.835
This next magician has more
than a few bright ideas

29:31.871 --> 29:34.238
to fool Penn and Teller.
Let's meet him.

29:34.273 --> 29:36.273
[fireworks crackling]

29:36.309 --> 29:37.441
<i>[funky music]</i>

29:37.476 --> 29:39.710
- I'm Ed Ripley.
I'm a magician,

29:39.745 --> 29:42.446
and I'm a nuclear metallurgist.

29:42.481 --> 29:44.315
<i>People don't understand
that scientists</i>

29:44.350 --> 29:46.617
<i>are all about creative play.
</i> [evil laughter]

29:46.652 --> 29:48.085
<i>If you don't enjoy
what you're doing,</i>

29:48.120 --> 29:50.287
<i>you're not gonna
be good at it.</i>

29:50.323 --> 29:52.990
<i>Science and magic originated
in the same place.</i>

29:53.025 --> 29:54.358
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:54.393 --> 29:56.694
<i>The original magicians
were alchemists</i>

29:56.729 --> 29:59.530
<i>trying to change lead
into gold.</i>

29:59.565 --> 30:03.067
I've spend my career trying
to exploit loopholes

30:03.102 --> 30:04.702
in the laws of physics.

30:04.737 --> 30:07.905
Because it's only when
you understand the rules

30:07.940 --> 30:09.773
that you're able
to break them.

30:09.809 --> 30:14.144
[cheering and applause]

30:14.180 --> 30:18.616
- Welcome the multi-talented
Ed Ripley!

30:18.651 --> 30:22.353
[cheering and applause]

30:22.388 --> 30:25.656
- It was Arthur C. Clarke
who said, "Any sufficiently

30:25.691 --> 30:29.093
advanced technology is
indistinguishable from magic."

30:29.128 --> 30:32.997
Well tonight, I'm going
to perform a classic of magic.

30:33.032 --> 30:35.633
But I'm not gonna use
any sleight of hand.

30:35.668 --> 30:37.501
Instead, I'm gonna use

30:37.536 --> 30:39.670
sufficiently advanced
technology,

30:39.705 --> 30:42.706
technology
that I developed myself.

30:42.742 --> 30:44.308
Alyson, would you mind
joining me?

30:44.343 --> 30:47.244
And if you would join me
as well.

30:47.279 --> 30:51.281
- Thank you.
[cheering and applause]

30:53.085 --> 30:54.618
- This...

30:54.654 --> 30:56.820
<i>[whimsical brass music]</i>

30:56.856 --> 30:59.523
is a printing machine.

30:59.558 --> 31:02.926
- Oh.
- But it also functions

31:02.962 --> 31:04.962
as an unprinting machine.

31:04.997 --> 31:07.831
Let me demonstrate.

31:07.867 --> 31:10.467
Any printed material
that goes in on this side

31:10.503 --> 31:14.672
will come out as a blank sheet
of paper on the other.

31:14.707 --> 31:19.476
So the red light indicates
that we are in unprint mode.

31:19.512 --> 31:23.480
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:23.516 --> 31:25.049
[audience amazement]

31:25.084 --> 31:27.117
Isn't that awesome?
I just turned

31:27.153 --> 31:30.087
a $100 bill
into a blank sheet of paper.

31:30.122 --> 31:31.755
[applause]

31:31.791 --> 31:34.091
[laughter]
Now you might ask why

31:34.126 --> 31:35.793
I would do such a thing.

31:35.828 --> 31:39.029
You may not have noticed it,
but I'm kind of a nerd,

31:39.065 --> 31:41.899
and I don't feel comfortable
carrying a lot of cash.

31:41.934 --> 31:44.068
But I can carry
all the paper I want.

31:44.103 --> 31:47.604
When I get to my destination,
I simply flip the switch...

31:47.640 --> 31:51.008
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:51.043 --> 31:53.944
And now it's in print mode.

31:53.979 --> 31:56.413
And just like my own
little ATM machine...

31:56.449 --> 31:57.614
[audience amazement]

31:57.650 --> 31:59.583
I have my hundred dollars back.

31:59.618 --> 32:04.588
[cheering and applause]

32:04.623 --> 32:07.624
Now, these are pieces
of currency

32:07.660 --> 32:09.626
from all over the world.

32:09.662 --> 32:11.962
If you notice,
they're different sizes,

32:11.997 --> 32:14.832
they're different colors,
they're different shapes.

32:14.867 --> 32:18.001
Um, you're welcome to choose
any that you like.

32:18.037 --> 32:19.336
Teller, would you please
choose one?

32:19.371 --> 32:22.773
Alyson, would you choose one?

32:22.808 --> 32:24.541
That's fine.

32:24.577 --> 32:26.276
- This one.
- Perfect.

32:26.312 --> 32:28.112
So, Alyson...
- Yes.

32:28.147 --> 32:31.048
- Do you know what this is?
- Paper.

32:31.083 --> 32:33.517
- You don't need to know
what it is, because the machine

32:33.552 --> 32:35.919
knows what it is for you.

32:35.955 --> 32:41.425
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:41.460 --> 32:43.460
[applause]

32:43.496 --> 32:45.362
- It's a five Kyat note

32:45.397 --> 32:47.097
from the Central Bank
of Myanmar.

32:47.133 --> 32:50.167
Here you go.
[applause]

32:50.202 --> 32:51.869
- [laughs]

32:51.904 --> 32:54.071
- And you don't need to know
what this one is, either.

32:54.106 --> 32:56.840
I think I have an idea.

32:56.876 --> 33:01.745
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:01.781 --> 33:03.714
[applause]
And Penn,

33:03.749 --> 33:07.384
this is a Polish 50 zloty
note--or is it 50 zlotys.

33:07.419 --> 33:11.588
Now, you may not
have realized it,

33:11.624 --> 33:15.459
but cash register receipt paper
is the same width

33:15.494 --> 33:17.161
as a dollar bill.
- Mm-hmm.

33:17.196 --> 33:19.797
- Now, I do experiments
for a living,

33:19.832 --> 33:22.232
and this is an experiment
that's just begging

33:22.268 --> 33:24.301
to be done.

33:24.336 --> 33:27.304
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:27.339 --> 33:28.872
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:28.908 --> 33:30.841
[audience amazement]

33:30.876 --> 33:33.076
[applause]

33:33.112 --> 33:34.411
Oh.

33:34.446 --> 33:37.915
The red ink means
we're running out of tape.

33:37.950 --> 33:39.817
[all gasp]
- Whoa!

33:39.852 --> 33:43.687
- Ah.
[cheering and applause]

33:43.722 --> 33:45.389
And...

33:45.424 --> 33:46.924
We don't have to worry
about this,

33:46.959 --> 33:48.492
I'll trim it off later.
[sniffs]

33:48.527 --> 33:52.196
Now, as I said,
this is a classic of magic

33:52.231 --> 33:53.564
um, I'm sure that you're
familiar with.

33:53.599 --> 33:57.267
As a matter of fact, I think
that there's one of these

33:57.303 --> 34:00.204
in the "Penn & Teller: Fool Us"
magic kit.

34:00.239 --> 34:01.705
- There is.
- So, Alyson...

34:01.740 --> 34:03.540
- Yes.
- You may not know

34:03.576 --> 34:05.576
how this works.
- No.

34:05.611 --> 34:07.211
- Get this thing apart.

34:07.246 --> 34:12.882
If you notice,
this is a solid.

34:12.918 --> 34:14.384
- Wow.
- Take it.

34:14.420 --> 34:17.254
- Okay.
- And this one...

34:17.289 --> 34:19.022
Is also solid.

34:19.058 --> 34:21.225
And this is a piece

34:21.260 --> 34:25.228
of sufficiently advanced
technology.

34:25.264 --> 34:27.797
Thank you very much.
- Wow.

34:27.833 --> 34:28.998
[applause]

34:29.034 --> 34:31.134
Ed Ripley!

34:31.170 --> 34:32.369
Wow!
[cheering and applause]

34:32.404 --> 34:34.271
- Take it all with you.
- I'm taking this.

34:34.306 --> 34:35.706
- Yeah. Here you go.

34:35.741 --> 34:38.976
All of it, yeah.

34:39.011 --> 34:40.710
- [amazed exclamation]

34:40.746 --> 34:42.846
Wow, that was incredible.

34:42.882 --> 34:44.815
I love that trick.

34:44.850 --> 34:48.118
And it would be very useful.
- It's tremendously useful.

34:48.152 --> 34:51.054
- Yes!
I mean, probably not legal.

34:51.090 --> 34:53.956
But useful.
[laughter]

34:53.993 --> 34:56.525
So magic is not
your full-time job.

34:56.562 --> 34:58.528
Who do you work for?
- So I work

34:58.564 --> 35:01.465
for the Y-12 Nucl--
National Security Complex

35:01.500 --> 35:03.300
in Oak Ridge,
and I've worked there

35:03.335 --> 35:05.502
for 28 years.
- And is it also true

35:05.537 --> 35:07.571
you have patented a lot
of products?

35:07.606 --> 35:10.173
- So I have 26 U.S. patents.

35:10.209 --> 35:12.075
- Wow.
- Uh, and several others

35:12.111 --> 35:14.278
that are in the process
of being patented.

35:14.313 --> 35:15.746
- That's incredible.
- Yep.

35:15.781 --> 35:17.681
- So your mind never stops.

35:17.716 --> 35:20.450
- I started my magic...

35:20.486 --> 35:22.552
44 years ago.
- Oh...

35:22.588 --> 35:25.022
- My grandmother knew
I was interested in magic,

35:25.057 --> 35:27.024
and she gave me
a hundred dollar bill

35:27.059 --> 35:28.959
in 1973...
- Whoa.

35:28.994 --> 35:32.329
And took me to Bob Hutching's
Magic Shack in Jacksonville.

35:32.364 --> 35:34.498
And that day I bought
the linking rings,

35:34.533 --> 35:37.935
the cups and balls, and a book
called "Bobo's Coin Magic."

35:37.970 --> 35:40.537
And I perform all three
of those tricks

35:40.572 --> 35:42.639
in my full-length shows
every time.

35:42.675 --> 35:45.042
So I'm one of the few people
I know that--

35:45.077 --> 35:47.044
the first tricks they bought
are the tricks

35:47.079 --> 35:49.746
that they still perform.
- And now you can make

35:49.782 --> 35:51.782
a hundred dollars
to pay your grandma back.

35:51.817 --> 35:53.750
- Yes, or--yeah.
[laughter]

35:53.786 --> 35:57.154
- Well, let's see if the boys
figured out your trick.

35:57.189 --> 35:59.122
- Well, Ed, let's start
with a question.

35:59.158 --> 36:01.291
Is this yours?
- Yes.

36:01.327 --> 36:02.960
- I don't mean you went
to a store and bought it,

36:02.995 --> 36:04.294
this is yours?
- Yeah, w--

36:04.330 --> 36:08.098
It was designed by me
and built with me and a friend

36:08.133 --> 36:10.867
who have a machine shop.
- Unbelievable.

36:10.903 --> 36:12.135
- Well, thank you.
- Just beau--

36:12.171 --> 36:14.137
What a beautiful prop.
[applause]

36:14.173 --> 36:17.007
I mean...
- Thank you.

36:17.042 --> 36:20.777
I mean, our magic set is nice,
but we know

36:20.813 --> 36:22.679
what magic props look like.
- Yeah.

36:22.715 --> 36:25.682
- This is not a magic prop,
this is a beautiful thing

36:25.718 --> 36:28.185
on every level.
It's just gorgeous.

36:28.220 --> 36:31.221
- Thank you.
- And we love, most of all,

36:31.256 --> 36:36.360
when someone takes a classic--
classic, um, magic plot

36:36.395 --> 36:41.231
and then just does it again,
and does it so, so beautifully.

36:41.266 --> 36:43.133
And, uh, you are--
you are a scientist,

36:43.168 --> 36:45.102
That's what you said, right?
- I am, I'm a--

36:45.137 --> 36:46.570
I'm a scientist, correct.
- Yeah.

36:46.605 --> 36:49.072
So performing you're--you're
a little bit nervous, right?

36:49.108 --> 36:53.010
I'm gonna use a little bit
of, um, jazz slang here

36:53.045 --> 36:54.544
instead of
the usual magic slang.

36:54.580 --> 36:56.380
But we thought you were gonna
fall into a ditch,

36:56.415 --> 36:57.614
but you're really
right in the pocket.

36:57.649 --> 37:00.951
I mean, just every single beat
was directly on.

37:00.986 --> 37:02.953
Now I'm a bass player,
so I know how important

37:02.988 --> 37:04.287
the pocket to a groove is.
- Yeah.

37:04.323 --> 37:05.956
- And it was just
all the way through--

37:05.991 --> 37:07.290
it was just fabulous.

37:07.326 --> 37:09.393
And we just loved it.

37:09.428 --> 37:10.594
And this prop--

37:10.629 --> 37:11.928
one of the most
beautiful things we've ever had

37:11.964 --> 37:13.430
on this show.
- Thank you.

37:13.465 --> 37:16.433
- Okay, so does that jazz lingo
mean they figured it out?

37:16.468 --> 37:18.935
- I think they figured it out.
- Aww, well, thank you.

37:18.971 --> 37:21.071
Ladies and gentlemen,
Ed Ripley!

37:21.106 --> 37:23.540
- Thank you.
- Really nice, Ed.

37:23.575 --> 37:26.276
[cheering and applause]

37:26.311 --> 37:28.011
- It's about time
for Penn and Teller

37:28.047 --> 37:30.147
to do some fooling
of their own.

37:30.182 --> 37:32.282
See them perform
after the break.

37:32.317 --> 37:35.285
<i>[jazz music]</i>

37:35.320 --> 37:37.254
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:39.091 --> 37:41.625
<i>[jazz music]</i>

37:41.660 --> 37:45.362
[cheering and applause]

37:45.397 --> 37:47.798
- Penn and Teller have built up
quite a collection

37:47.833 --> 37:50.534
of devious tricks
and marvelous masterpieces

37:50.569 --> 37:52.302
over their 40-year history.

37:52.337 --> 37:54.037
Tonight, they'll unveil one

37:54.073 --> 37:55.972
of their most
prized possessions.

37:56.008 --> 37:58.675
Welcome
your confounding curators,

37:58.710 --> 38:00.610
Penn and Teller!

38:00.646 --> 38:02.179
- Thank you.
[cheering and applause]

38:02.214 --> 38:04.548
You know, um--
You know Johnny Thompson.

38:04.583 --> 38:06.116
- Oh, yes.
- Johnny Thompson's our mentor.

38:06.151 --> 38:07.517
He works with us all the time.

38:07.553 --> 38:08.885
He's also the big boss.

38:08.921 --> 38:10.887
He's the judge--to listen
to everything we say.

38:10.923 --> 38:12.122
He knows how
all the tricks are done.

38:12.157 --> 38:14.691
He decides whether
we've been fooled or not.

38:14.726 --> 38:17.794
He's the final decision.
And this is the stage

38:17.830 --> 38:20.530
he toured carnivals with, uh,

38:20.566 --> 38:22.732
in the '70s,
all over the USA,

38:22.768 --> 38:25.135
and, uh, Mexico and Canada.

38:25.170 --> 38:27.671
And we've replaced almost all
of it, piece by piece.

38:27.706 --> 38:30.240
But, uh, wanna show you--
there's a trap door

38:30.275 --> 38:33.110
built in here, if Teller can--
Teller can find it here.

38:33.145 --> 38:34.411
So this is what he could use.

38:34.446 --> 38:36.313
I mean, even though
he's working outside

38:36.348 --> 38:37.647
of the fair, he can use
the trap door.

38:37.683 --> 38:38.782
He could sneak someone
out here.

38:38.817 --> 38:39.850
- Hi.
- And come over here, Alyson,

38:39.885 --> 38:41.251
we'll show you--
right up behind it,

38:41.286 --> 38:43.620
there's real '70s Mylar here.
I can help you up there.

38:43.655 --> 38:44.788
- Whoo.
- Walk right--

38:44.823 --> 38:46.523
walk right over there.
But see the, uh--

38:46.558 --> 38:48.758
Then there's a skull
set up over here

38:48.794 --> 38:50.327
for his ventriloquist act.

38:50.362 --> 38:51.628
And you pull this, and he--

38:51.663 --> 38:53.096
[goofy voice]
Hi, there, how are you?

38:53.132 --> 38:54.798
[laughter]
It, uh--it talks, see?

38:54.833 --> 38:56.233
- Wow.
- "I'm a dead guy."

38:56.268 --> 38:57.501
- That's amazing.
- Yep.

38:57.536 --> 38:58.869
And he would do
a whole routine with there.

38:58.904 --> 38:59.936
But the best thing
we want to show you--

38:59.972 --> 39:01.037
Let me get down first
so I can--

39:01.073 --> 39:02.372
I can help you, here.
- Aw, thank you.

39:02.407 --> 39:04.908
- The best thing there, Alyson,
is this mirror cabinet.

39:04.943 --> 39:07.344
And you know the expression
in, uh--in magic,

39:07.379 --> 39:08.545
that it's all done
with mirrors?

39:08.580 --> 39:10.647
- Yeah.
- Well, sometimes it is.

39:10.682 --> 39:13.316
Here's a cabinet
that Johnny could use to, uh--

39:13.352 --> 39:15.085
It's
Great Tomsoni and Company.

39:15.120 --> 39:16.653
He could vanish company.

39:16.688 --> 39:19.022
He'd close the doors like this,

39:19.057 --> 39:21.658
and then some sort
of magic gesture,

39:21.693 --> 39:23.293
Abracadabra,
or whatever you want.

39:23.328 --> 39:26.363
And then the box
is completely empty.

39:26.398 --> 39:27.364
[audience amazement]
- Wow.

39:27.399 --> 39:28.365
- We thought we'd, uh...

39:28.400 --> 39:30.000
[applause]

39:30.035 --> 39:33.136
If we were trying to bust this,
we'd notice the, uh,

39:33.172 --> 39:34.471
the stripes here...
- Oh-hoh-hoh.

39:34.506 --> 39:36.339
- And the fact
that the angles in front--

39:36.375 --> 39:37.908
And there's a mirror there,
you just pull it--

39:37.943 --> 39:41.178
You can see it move, there.
It reflects this as the side;

39:41.213 --> 39:43.146
you think it's the back.
And if you look at it--

39:43.182 --> 39:44.714
you know,
mirrors do all this stuff.

39:44.750 --> 39:47.350
If you can crouch down
a little bit, sometimes

39:47.386 --> 39:49.052
the mirror will give you--
like, a fun-house mirror.

39:49.087 --> 39:50.353
- Oh, yeah.
- It gives you

39:50.389 --> 39:51.788
a different angle.
So in this case,

